      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver with documented QA procedures and version control meets MRL 2 requirements.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 19.2 was used with institutional license management. Release notes, bug-fix documentation, and regression test suite are available from the vendor. Version was fixed throughout the study and recorded in the simulation log. QA level is consistent with MRL 2 expectations for a Class II device."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmark results against known analytical solutions for laminar pipe flow and lid-driven cavity are available and show errors below 1%.",
      "rationale": "Standard benchmark cases (Poiseuille flow, lid-driven cavity at Re=400) were reproduced with errors below 0.5% against analytical and published reference solutions. These are included in the solver's published verification suite and are sufficient for MRL 2 code verification."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) reported for all primary QoIs using at least three systematically refined meshes; extrapolated solution within 2% of finest-mesh result.",
      "rationale": "A mesh sensitivity study was conducted using two mesh refinement levels (coarse and fine, approximately 2.1M and 5.4M cells). The fine-mesh hemolysis index differed from the coarse-mesh result by less than 8%, which was judged by the assessment team to be acceptable given the engineering conservatism applied to the RH threshold. A formal Richardson extrapolation using a third mesh level was not completed due to computational resource constraints, but the team considers the observed trend sufficient for design guidance purposes."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, hematocrit) are documented and match nominal CFD boundary conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA GCBP bench test data were collected at five operating points (2–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM). Fluid temperature was maintained at 37±0.5°C; hematocrit at 30±1%. Boundary conditions in the CFD model were set to the nominal experimental values. Measurement uncertainties were documented in the test report."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against experimental NIH at all five operating points; mean absolute error below 25%.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH values were within 18% of experimental measurements across all five operating points. The worst-case operating condition (4 L/min, 3500 RPM) was correctly identified by the model. Comparison plots and tabulated errors are included in the V&V report appendix."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (NIH, volume-averaged scalar stress) are directly traceable to the COU decision metric (RH < 1).",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis and volume-averaged scalar shear stress are the primary QoIs. Both are directly used in computing the relative hemolysis index RH, which is the regulatory acceptance criterion. The mapping from QoI to decision metric is explicitly documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
